<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
KEPT AS A WARNING — do not point FASTRTPS_DEFAULT_PROFILES_FILE at this file on
TROS unless you have read all of the below. It is here because working this out
cost an evening.

The problem it was written for: with the full NAVIGATE graph up, goal_navigator's
/cmd_vel publishes began failing outright —

    RCLError: Failed to publish: cannot publish data, at ./src/rmw_publish.cpp:62

~21 failures in 24 s. The commands never left the node, so the wheels never
moved and the robot looked "stuck" while the navigator believed it was driving.

The ACTUAL cause was not the transport: Fast-DDS leaks its /dev/shm
data-sharing segments whenever a node is SIGKILLed (a launch that ignores
SIGINT, an agent restart under a running mode). They pile up across mode
switches — 569 stale segments after one evening of testing — until Fast-DDS
runs out of segment bookkeeping and refuses to publish. /dev/shm was only 13 MB
of 2.6 GB used, so it never looks like exhaustion by size. The fix lives in
app/agent/run_agent.sh: sweep stale segments when nothing is using DDS.

Why disabling shared memory here is the WRONG fix on this platform:

  * TROS ships hobot_shm, which hooks FASTRTPS_DEFAULT_PROFILES_FILE for
    zero-copy and forces RMW_FASTRTPS_USE_QOS_FROM_XML=1. Setting the variable
    hands your XML the job of defining ALL writer/reader QoS.
  * A profile that omits data_writer/data_reader therefore leaves every writer
    with unusable buffers, and each C++ node aborts on startup:
        terminate called after throwing an instance of
        'eprosima::fastcdr::exception::NotEnoughMemoryException'
        what():  Not enough memory in the buffer stream
    rclpy nodes survive, so the launch half-dies in a very confusing way —
    15 nodes dead, agent still happily running.
  * The namespace must be exactly the one below. With
    xmlns="http://www.eprosima.com" the file is rejected and every C++
    participant aborts with SIGABRT, same symptom, different reason.

If you ever do need SHM off, start from hobot's own profile
(/opt/tros/humble/lib/hobot_shm/config/shm_fastdds.xml) and change only
<data_sharing> to OFF, keeping its PREALLOCATED_WITH_REALLOC history policy and
ASYNCHRONOUS publish mode — that is what the writers need to allocate sanely.
-->
<profiles xmlns="http://www.eprosima.com/XMLSchemas/fastRTPS_Profiles">
    <transport_descriptors>
        <transport_descriptor>
            <transport_id>udp_only</transport_id>
            <type>UDPv4</type>
        </transport_descriptor>
    </transport_descriptors>

    <participant profile_name="no_shm_participant" is_default_profile="true">
        <rtps>
            <userTransports>
                <transport_id>udp_only</transport_id>
            </userTransports>
            <useBuiltinTransports>false</useBuiltinTransports>
        </rtps>
    </participant>

    <!-- these two are what the minimal version was missing -->
    <data_writer profile_name="default publisher profile" is_default_profile="true">
        <qos>
            <publishMode>
                <kind>ASYNCHRONOUS</kind>
            </publishMode>
            <data_sharing>
                <kind>OFF</kind>
            </data_sharing>
        </qos>
        <historyMemoryPolicy>PREALLOCATED_WITH_REALLOC</historyMemoryPolicy>
    </data_writer>

    <data_reader profile_name="default subscription profile" is_default_profile="true">
        <qos>
            <data_sharing>
                <kind>OFF</kind>
            </data_sharing>
        </qos>
        <historyMemoryPolicy>PREALLOCATED_WITH_REALLOC</historyMemoryPolicy>
    </data_reader>
</profiles>
